Observation Details: Continuing bird found yesterday (12/2) by W. Legge. Thank you yet again, William! Initially, Alex picked it up in the willows in the south side of Mitchell Rd. (north side of lagoon) near the “Park Parallel” sign across from the Nature Bridge campus. We lost it fairly quickly and could not refind it until awhile later when it almost flew right over us both on Kirkpatrick St. near building T1044. We followed it to the roped off section near the volleyball court here (37.8326834, -122.5347095), where we eventually enjoyed great views as it foraged actively. We were soon joined by others, who all had solid looks at the bird in the same general vicinity.   Superficially, reminiscent of an empid (WIFL), but overall larger, darker uppers, dark head/crown and face, dark tail, and all black bill. Phoebe-type behavior, constantly tail-wagging. A really good bird for the county, the first since 2017 and the first chaseable one in over a decade(?). Enjoyed an absolutely lovely Marin Phoebe trifecta.

Observation Details: Finally found the Eastern Phoebe along the perimeter fence at 33° 50'34"N, 118° 11'9"W +-13' where it flew onto the power lines by the power pole at these coordinates then about 15minutes later it flew over to a wood railing near the lake where we took most of our pics.  This bird frequently wagged its tail and sallied out and back several times from its position on the power line into a pine tree and back.  This bird didn't have the dark neck like our black phoebe- the white under its neck wrapped around under the cheek.  This eastern phoebe was a grayish taupe color on his back and tail.  Light colored belly with a hint of a pale yellow wash on the bottom. Our Black Phoebe here has a much darker head and overall color- they both share similar looking bills and leg color.  Pics will be added

Continues from yesterday’s initial report - foraging from fencelines and tall weedy stalks on N side of entrance trail. Call note similar to BLPH, but softer, less sharp. A much smaller, relatively compact, short-tailed phoebe compared to the SAPHs that regularly displaced it.  Dark brown upperparts and head that includes the and upper 2/3 of face (including eye and to lower limit of auriculars). Underparts including throat and lower portion of face, mostly cream white with hint of yellow, depending on lighting, with darker sides. Faint paler tips on coverts and edges of tertials add slight contrast and create a slight pattern on its otherwise near monochrome upperoarts.   Photos tba

Initially reported by Jade Goodman (thanks, Jade!), the phoebe was working along the fence just NW of the end of the cul-de-sac between the parking lot and the fire station, about here: 33.654437, -117.783185 (accuracy: 22 ft). Thanks to Tom W. for pointing me in the right direction. Watched the bird for over 30 minutes. It spent most of the time on the fence, but would occasionally fly down to the ground to get a snack. It was continually flicking its tail. During the time I watched the Eastern phoebe was chased off its perch four times by an aggressive Say's phoebe. Three times the Eastern phoebe would fly into the nearby trees, but would shortly return to the fence. Toward the end of my visit, the phoebe was vocalizing almost continually, just a soft 'chip' every second or so.

The bird, sometimes skittish, called and perched often on fences and brush, always moving its tail. Brownish above and pale yellowy below, its throat was also pale yellowy. Its sporadic "chip" was high, clear, but not as soft as that of a Black Phoebe.

Observation Details: While walking the shoreline of Lake Tamarisk we came across a phoebe that was perched quietly on a chair atop a barge in the western corner of the lake.  We soon realized that it was an Eastern Phoebe and then spent a short time observing this bird and taking photos as it moved about structures along the shore, the stalks of a small stand of bulrushes, the shoreline, and a few nearby trees.  I did not think I ever heard this bird call, but I did hear a Black Phoebe calling nearby.  This bird typically perched low and in the open between its flights so it was easily observed, but it did not permit an overly close approach.  I think I saw this bird dip its tail a few times, but it did not do this extensively. This was a small to medium-sized flycatcher that was typical of a phoebe in its size and structure.  The bill was slim and relatively short, in that it would have extended backward on the face to a point just behind the eye.  The head was unremarkable size with a sloping forehead, a gently rounded crown, and seemingly a weakly peaked appearance to the rear part of the crown.  The neck was short and inconspicuous, and the body was relatively plump, full-chested, and with an upright posture.  The wings were relatively short, with a primary projection that was about one-third the length of the exposed secondaries and the wingtips reaching to the tips of the uppertail coverts.  I counted the tips of five primaries exposed  beyond the longest secondary in the rounded wingtip.  The tail was almost as long as the head and body combined, it was slightly flared, and with a weakly notched tip.  I further thought the rectrices visible from below that pointed tips.  The legs were short and of unremarkable mass. This was a subtly marked bird with relatively dull patterns.  The head was dark, but I am now less sure about the precise color.  If pressed, I would have thought the head was dark brownish, possibly with a grayish or olive cast and with the face appearing more sooty in coloration.  I noted no suggestion of either an eyeing or supercilium.  The solidly dark coloration of the face appeared to extend down to the lower edge of the moustachial and auricular regions, but below this the submoustachial region was clouded darker, which resulted in some degree of blending between the dark face and the cream-colored throat.  The creamy-whitish color of the throat contrasted with a dusky wash at the sides of the breast and foreflanks that nearly pinched off the pale color in the center, below which the belly, rear flanks, and undertail coverts were a pale yellow in color.  I think the underside of the tail was uniformly dark, but I did not see it all that well.  The back and sides of the neck were dusky in coloration, but the back and scapulars were a medium, grayish-olive in color and without pattern.  The wings contrasted as darker than the back given sooty centers to the coverts and remiges.  The greater and median coverts were each fringed with a light, olive-gray color that produced a scaly upper wingbar and a more diffuse lower wingbar that combined a narrow edge and a somewhat broader tip to each feather.  The remiges were also edges paler.  I thought the innermost secondaries had well-defined edges of white, but the edges on the remaining feathers were more grayish to yellowish-olive and seemingly narrower and less conspicuous.  I cannot now recall if the edges were less conspicuous on the primaries and I have no recollection about seeing the primary coverts.  The exposed primary tips were sooty to blackish I color and without conspicuous fringing.  I am not sure I ever saw the rump or uppertail coverts, but the upperside of the tail was sooty in coloration and without obvious fringes. The bill, legs, and feet appeared to be entirely black.  The eyes, were dark, but I was unable to discern any color.

Observation Details: Continuing for a few days now. Same area as initially reported, flying in ravine, as well as darting back and forth across road. The bird, sometimes skittish, called and perched often on fences and brush, always moving its tail. Brownish above and pale yellowy below, its throat was also pale yellowy. It had dullish wingbars, a black bill and black legs, and a brownish wash on its flanks. The tail had a prominent notch and its head appeared long and rounded toward its forehead with a slight peak at the top back of its head. Its sporadic "chip" was high, clear, but not as soft as that of a Black Phoebe.

Observation Details: Continuing rarity originally found by Michael Rieser in October and in the same vicinity working the treatment plant eucalyptus and fence line. I recorded 3 calls with Merlin, which gave me only one choice of ID each time, EAPH. After watching it flycatch it disappeared, but then I heard a call I was not familiar with hearing in Monterey (#1 recording). Then we refound the EAPH sitting on the fence and watched it chip (#2 recording). Shortly after, it was heard only chipping again (#3 recording). At the time I only heard one BLPH before discovering the EAPH and it was farther away in a different direction. The EAPH was mostly at fence height or on the ground although once it was seen briefly fairly high in the eucalyptus. Unfortunately, the treatment plants’ constant deep hum is heard in the recordings.

Locality: Southern Glades Trail (C111 Canal outside ENP)

Observation Details: Continuing, found by Rebecca Matsubara two days prior. Refound today in the previously reported location, on the path near the picnic table near the Grangers’ Wharf parking lot. Around here: (38.020602, -122.142031). Actively flycatching in this area for the half-hour-plus that I observed it. It moved around the general area, ranging from the path to the trees and shrubs to the fence. This bird was a typical phoebe, a large flycatcher constantly pumping its tail. The Eastern was slightly larger than the Black Phoebes in the area, but significantly smaller than the Say’s. It had a dark head which significantly contrasted with its white throat. The white throat wrapped slightly around in the back, reminding me of a classic Myrtle Warbler auricular wrap. The underparts were white with a slight gray-brown vested appearance, and a yellow wash on the belly. The wings, back and tail were all a mostly even gray-brown. Two faint wingbars were visible on a slightly darker-brown wing. I have never seen an Eastern Phoebe before, but from what I can tell this is a rather bright individual. The bird was silent the whole time I observed it, even when local Black Phoebes were actively calling. Photos, and a lifer!!

Observation Details: Continuing. Hanging out between the YMCA building and the alley wall. Coordinates on this checklist location.  Warm brown above, darker head, pale white throat and belly, dull wingbars and faint yellow wash seen on belly. Medium tail, constant wagging. Sometimes the bird shows a peaked head.  Heard vocalizing a few times.   Tail-wagging video  https://youtu.be/QH4X08etUjg?feature=shared  *** Episode 1 earlier in the morning in checklist below along with other birds noted  https://ebird.org/checklist/S205865803

Continuing for a few days now. Same area as initially reported, flying in ravine, as well as darting back and forth across road. The bird, sometimes skittish, called and perched often on fences and brush, always moving its tail. Brownish above and pale yellowy below, its throat was also pale yellowy. It had dullish wingbars, a black bill and black legs, and a brownish wash on its flanks. The tail had a prominent notch and its head appeared long and rounded toward its forehead with a slight peak at the top back of its head. Its sporadic "chip" was high, clear, but not as soft as that of a Black Phoebe.

Initially reported by Jade Goodman (thanks, Jade!), the phoebe was working along the fence just NW of the end of the cul-de-sac between the parking lot and the fire station, about here: 33.654437, -117.783185 (accuracy: 22 ft). Thanks to Tom W. for pointing me in the right direction. Watched the bird for over 30 minutes. It spent most of the time on the fence, but would occasionally fly down to the ground to get a snack. It was continually flicking its tail. During the time I watched the Eastern phoebe was chased off its perch four times by an aggressive Say's phoebe. Three times the Eastern phoebe would fly into the nearby trees, but would shortly return to the fence. Toward the end of my visit, the phoebe was vocalizing almost continually, just a soft 'chip' every second or so.

Continuing well documented Eastern cutie. Thank you very much, Jade Goodman!! for this cute East Coast refresher and a chance for me to get better documentation.  Brownish above, brown tail, light yellow wash on belly, pale white below, lighter wing bars, orange tongue (captured few times :-)) and darker cap. Overall colors seem to change with lighting, light browner shades turning into much darker shades and darker cap.  On the fence between trail entrance and the fire station. SAPHs and sometimes So Cal winds were not very friendly to our visitor, but eventually, EAPH was left alone. The bird also made a circuit a few times. Got a few pictures with a background of mountains. The rest of the documentation is in the photos, videos, and audio :) Photos of eating bugs and a 180-degree fly-catching.  Video of blowing winds almost rooting off the bird:  https://youtu.be/-kxo__8O2NU?feature=shared  Video of calls:  https://youtu.be/r8wRsYZlOw4?feature=shared  Some slomo flying:  https://youtu.be/kpsW4fB7V1o?feature=shared

Continues from yesterday’s initial report - foraging from fencelines and tall weedy stalks on N side of entrance trail. Call note similar to BLPH, but softer, less sharp. A much smaller, relatively compact, short-tailed phoebe compared to the SAPHs that regularly displaced it.  Dark brown upperparts and head that includes the and upper 2/3 of face (including eye and to lower limit of auriculars). Underparts including throat and lower portion of face, mostly cream white with hint of yellow, depending on lighting, with darker sides. Faint paler tips on coverts and edges of tertials add slight contrast and create a slight pattern on its otherwise near monochrome upperoarts.   Photos tba

Found yesterday by Jade Goodman. Thanks, Jade! Seen today from here: (33.6543924, -117.7835378). Left side of trail entrance, about 100 feet. Very confiding. Perches for long periods. Wags tail down. Vermilionesque in stature. Pale yellow wash on lower belly. More white on front than Black Phoebe. Quite vocal. Definitely cuter! Seen w Shirley R, Sylvia A, Steve N, and David O.

Initially reported by Jade Goodman (thanks, Jade!), the phoebe was working along the fence just NW of the end of the cul-de-sac between the parking lot and the fire station, about here: 33.654437, -117.783185 (accuracy: 22 ft). Thanks to Tom W. for pointing me in the right direction. Watched the bird for over 30 minutes. It spent most of the time on the fence, but would occasionally fly down to the ground to get a snack. It was continually flicking its tail. During the time I watched the Eastern phoebe was chased off its perch four times by an aggressive Say's phoebe. Three times the Eastern phoebe would fly into the nearby trees, but would shortly return to the fence. Toward the end of my visit, the phoebe was vocalizing almost continually, just a soft 'chip' every second or so.

One bird was seen on a branch over one of the large ponds and the other was seen on a branch in the middle of the park, probably 100 yards away from water, but not the same pond as the other Phoebe.  The sightings were probably 200-300 yards and over 30 minutes apart.  It is possible it is the same bird as they were very similar in appearance but I am treating them as two separate birds. Observation Details: 5 babies being dutifully fed by brave parents, enduring despite choosing a nest under a human structure. I ended up closer than I preferred to be as I can't be in the direct sunlight forever and the birds and I were all panting in the heat, so I took breaks under the shelter and kept as far away from them as I could. Then a whole huge group of people showed up and filled the shelter, but the parents still managed. I will never get over how fast they grow.   I can see from my photos that there is a mite infestation and one of the babies is covered in them. I hope the little ones make it ok.

Woohoo!! Spring is in the air. While standing on the NE side of Sugar Pond, I heard an unfamiliar chip call that I kept thinking might be WIWR but sounded to prolonged. I couldn’t pinpoint where the bird was at first but eventually realized it was near the wooden footbridge. Before I could begin walking, a bird shot in front of me and landed about 10ft away: Phoebe indeed! Pumped its tail and called for some time before getting closer to the waters’ edge. It proceeded northward through the woods and began singing famous “fee-bee” song near Sugar Pond Swamp. Also wonderful to have back.

After sheltering under the Riverside bridge during a rain shower, I entered the eastern section of the park to see if I could locate the wintering Eastern Phoebe.  After walking around the small Oak trees near the bridge, I spotted it in the lower branches of an Oak, just to my west.  I was able to follow it to the saplings near the bridge opening and then onto the faux wood fence, before it flew off toward the river.

Observation Details: Continuing bird; this is the third winter it's been in my yard. I obtained video of the singing, but eBird doesn't support .mov files.  I sighted the bird fly-catching and when it roosted, characteristic tail-bobbing.  Dusky dark gray on head, back, and upper tail coverts, dark eye, bill, and legs; light-colored chin, breast, and under-tail coverts.  I obtained some rather poor photos.

Continuing, found by Rebecca Matsubara two days prior. Refound today in the previously reported location, on the path near the picnic table near the Grangers’ Wharf parking lot. Around here: (38.020602, -122.142031). Actively flycatching in this area for the half-hour-plus that I observed it. It moved around the general area, ranging from the path to the trees and shrubs to the fence. This bird was a typical phoebe, a large flycatcher constantly pumping its tail. The Eastern was slightly larger than the Black Phoebes in the area, but significantly smaller than the Say’s. It had a dark head which significantly contrasted with its white throat. The white throat wrapped slightly around in the back, reminding me of a classic Myrtle Warbler auricular wrap. The underparts were white with a slight gray-brown vested appearance, and a yellow wash on the belly. The wings, back and tail were all a mostly even gray-brown. Two faint wingbars were visible on a slightly darker-brown wing. I have never seen an Eastern Phoebe before, but from what I can tell this is a rather bright individual. The bird was silent the whole time I observed it, even when local Black Phoebes were actively calling. Photos, and a lifer!!

Observation Details: Curtis Marantz and I returned to look for this bird I'd seen briefly during yesterday's Morro Bay CBC. We found the bird in the same location (about 150 yards south of Bianchi Lane) after looking for it for a while. The bird was in the riparian strip between Hwy 101 and San Luis Obispo Creek. This area is signed as City Open Space. The bird's head was darker than the gray-brown back, wings and tail. It was pale below with a whitish throat, had a weak streaky vest, and had a pale yellow belly and undertail coverts. The pale tips of the wing covers created faint wingbars. The bill and eyes were dark.  Photos

Observation Details: 5 babies being dutifully fed by brave parents, enduring despite choosing a nest under a human structure. I ended up closer than I preferred to be as I can't be in the direct sunlight forever and the birds and I were all panting in the heat, so I took breaks under the shelter and kept as far away from them as I could. Then a whole huge group of people showed up and filled the shelter, but the parents still managed. I will never get over how fast they grow.   I can see from my photos that there is a mite infestation and one of the babies is covered in them. I hope the little ones make it ok.

(34.1299573, -117.7944637) Scott heard the bird call when we first entered the large open grassy field full of sunflowers so we went counterclockwise over towards the grove of pine trees and walked around, and Scott heard the bird a second time, which was when we got audio recordings and photos of it. This bird is a greenish grayish version of a Black Phoebe without the obvious demarcations where the white and black end. Instead, this bird has a dark face and dark eyes and a small, dark bill, that transitions into a paler throat and smudgy chest with no clear pattern. The bird was singing, and it was clearly not the song of either a Black Phoebe, or a Say’s Phoebe albeit closer to Black Phoebe.

Finally! Seen 37.663576,-121.901974 White throat, yellowish belly, charcoal grey above. Phoebe-shaped. Disappeared before I could get close enough for a photo  Reappeared 37.662405,-121.905843 ( more or less the place most people have seen it, near the confluence of the two channels) at 2:15, allowed photos while it preened. This time could see the rounded head, pale grey wrapping up the sides of the neck a bit. Very thin faint wingbars and almost myiarchus-style fringing. Would bounce tail down and up after sallying. Finally! Seen 37.663576,-121.901974 White throat, yellowish belly, charcoal grey above. Phoebe-shaped.
